          "title": "The divinely revealed pattern — temple plans as scripture",
          "body": "The transfer of plans in verses 11-18 is often read as administrative detail, but the Chronicler's theological point is carried in verse 19: 'All this,' said David, 'the LORD made me understand in writing by His hand upon me, all the details of this pattern.' The word *tavnit* (pattern, plan) used three times (28:11, 12, 18) is the same word Exodus uses for the heavenly pattern Moses received for the tabernacle (Exodus 25:9, 40). By echoing that terminology, the Chronicler makes a precise claim: David's temple plans are not a human architectural vision but a divinely communicated revelation. The temple is not Israel's monument to God; it is God's self-disclosure in architectural form. The detailed inventory of utensils, lampstands, tables, bowls, forks, and the gold-covered cherubim of the chariot-throne (28:11-18) is not bureaucratic record-keeping; it is the physical vocabulary in which God has chosen to express His holiness, His glory, and His approachability through the sacrificial system. Solomon's task is not creative design but faithful execution of a received revelation."
