          "body": "The chapter closes in verses 20-21 with a deliberately Deuteronomic-Josianic cadence. 'Be strong and courageous, and act; do not fear nor be dismayed' echoes Deuteronomy 31:6-7, 23 and Joshua 1:6, 7, 9 almost verbatim — the triple command given to Moses for Joshua, and to Joshua for the conquest. By framing Solomon's building commission with the same language as the conquest commission, the Chronicler signals that temple-building is a form of holy warfare: taking possession of God's dwelling place on earth against all the forces of discouragement, inadequacy, and fear. The ground for courage is stated with personal intensity: 'the LORD God, *my* God, is with you.' David does not say 'your God' but 'my God' — the God who accompanied David through wilderness, warfare, and failure is the same God who accompanies Solomon into the construction project. The promise — 'He will not fail you nor forsake you' — is deliberately echoed in Hebrews 13:5, where it becomes the permanent ground of contentment for every New Testament believer. The closing verse (28:21) then names the human provisions God supplies: organized priests and Levites, skilled willing workers, and the full support of the officials and the people. Divine presence does not render human collaboration unnecessary; it makes that collaboration available and coherent."
